{
  "doc_id": "23062",
  "text": "As a key regulator of NAD + biosynthesis, NAMPT has received considerable attention in recent years and is deemed to be a potential cancer therapeutic target. [CITATION_1] There is evidence that NAMPT activity promotes cell proliferation and survival following genotoxic stress, suggesting that it can function as an oncoprotein under certain conditions. [CITATION_2] Indeed, overexpression of NAMPT has been observed in many cancers, including colorectal cancer, breast cancer, gastric cancer, prostate cancer, ovarian cancer, oesophageal cancer and lymphoma. [CITATION_3] The progrowth and -survival nature of NAMPT has been attributed primarily to its function as an NAMPT, as FK866, a highly specific non-competitive inhibitor of NAMPT presently undergoing clinical trials, can effectively reduce the intracellular NAD + pool, resulting in cell death.",
